Session of 2025
SENATE BILL No. 105
By Committee on Federal and State Affairs
1-29
1 AN ACT concerning the offices of United States senator, state treasurer
2 and the commissioner of insurance; relating to the filling of vacancies
3 in such offices; requiring the appointment of a person of the same
4 political party as the incumbent; requiring the legislature to nominate
5 three persons for consideration for such appointment and that the
6 governor appoint one of the nominated persons; establishing the joint
7 committee on vacancy appointments; amending K.S.A. 25-101b and
8 40-106 and repealing the existing sections; also repealing K.S.A. 25-
9 318.
10
11 Be it enacted by the Legislature of the State of Kansas:
12 New Section 1. (a) Upon a vacancy occurring in the office of United
13 States senator from this state, the governor shall make a temporary
14 appointment to fill such vacancy until a successor is elected and qualified.
15 Such temporary appointment shall be made in accordance with the
16 provisions of sections 2 through 4, and amendments thereto. Within two
17 three calendar days after receiving a concurrent resolution adopted
18 pursuant to section 4, and amendments thereto, or a report submitted
19 pursuant to section 3, and amendments thereto, the governor shall appoint
20 one of the three persons recommended as candidates in such concurrent
21 resolution or report to temporarily fill such vacancy. Except as otherwise
22 provided, at the time of the next election of representatives in congress
23 immediately following such vacancy, such vacancy shall be filled by
24 election and the senator so elected shall take office upon receiving such
25 senator's certificate of election. If the vacancy occurs on or after May 1
26 in an even-numbered year, then such vacancy shall be filled by election
27 at the election of representatives in congress held two years following
28 the year in which such vacancy occurs.
29 (b) No person shall be appointed pursuant to this act unless such
30 person is a resident of this state and shall have been registered with the
31 same political party for the immediately preceding six years as that of the
32 United States senator elected at the immediately preceding election for
33 such office. If the United States senator elected at the immediately
34 preceding election for such office was not registered with any political

SB 105—Am. by SCW 2
1 party, then any suitable person who is a resident of this state may be
2 appointed pursuant to sections 2 through 4, and amendments thereto.
3 (c) No person appointed pursuant to subsection (a) shall take office
4 unless such appointment is certified by the secretary of state to the
5 United States senate. The secretary shall not certify any person as being
6 appointed to fill a vacancy in the office of United States senator unless
7 such person is appointed in accordance with this section.
8 New Sec. 2. (a) Except as otherwise provided, within 10 calendar
9 days of a vacancy occurring in the office of United States senator, the
10 office of state treasurer or the office of the commissioner of insurance, the
11 joint committee on vacancy appointments shall be established by
12 appointment of the members of the joint committee. Each of this state's
13 congressional districts shall be represented by at least two members of the
14 joint committee who shall be residents thereof. The joint committee shall
15 consist of 12 members as follows:
16 (1) The president of the senate, or a member of the senate designated
17 by the president;
18 (2) one member of the senate appointed by the president;
19 (3) the speaker of the house of representatives, or a member of the
20 house of representatives designated by the speaker;
21 (4) one member of the house of representatives appointed by the
22 speaker;
23 (5) two members of the senate appointed by the majority leader of the
24 senate;
25 (6) two members of the house of representatives appointed by the
26 majority leader of the house of representatives;
27 (7) one member of the senate appointed by the vice president of the
28 senate;
29 (8) one member of the house of representatives appointed by the
30 speaker pro tem of the house of representatives;
31 (9) one member of the senate appointed by the minority leader of the
32 senate; and
33 (10) one member of the house of representatives appointed by the
34 minority leader of the house of representatives.
35 (b) Of the members named or appointed under subsections (a)(1),
36 (a)(2), (a)(5) and (a)(7), each of this state's congressional districts shall
37 be represented by at least one such member who shall be a resident
38 thereof. Of the members named or appointed under subsections (a)(3),
39 (a)(4), (a)(6) and (a)(8), each of this state's congressional districts shall
40 be represented by at least one such member who shall be a resident
41 thereof.
42 (c) The joint committee on vacancy appointments shall not be
43 established when a vacancy occurs less than 90 calendar days prior to

SB 105—Am. by SCW 3
1 December 31 in any year in which a general election for such office is
2 held, unless the person vacating such office was elected to such office at
3 such general election and was an incumbent in such election.
4 (c)(d) The president of the senate, or the president's designee, shall be
5 the chairperson of the joint committee and the speaker of the house of
6 representatives, or the speaker's designee, shall be the vice chairperson.
7 The vice chairperson shall exercise all the powers of the chairperson in the
8 absence of the chairperson.
9 (d)(e) The joint committee on vacancy appointments shall meet at any
10 time and at any place within the state on call of the chairperson. Members
11 of the joint committee shall receive compensation and travel expenses and
12 subsistence expenses or allowances as provided in K.S.A. 75-3212, and
13 amendments thereto, when attending meetings of such committee.
14 (e)(f) The first meeting of the joint committee shall be held within 30
15 calendar days of a vacancy occurring in the office of United States
16 senator, the office of state treasurer or the office of the commissioner of
17 insurance.
18 New Sec. 3. (a) The joint committee on vacancy appointments shall
19 review candidates to fill the vacancy described in section 2, and
20 amendments thereto. Such review shall include verifying that such
21 candidate satisfies federal and state requirements to hold such office and to
22 be appointed to fill a vacancy in such office. The joint committee shall
23 conduct one or more public hearings and shall grant each candidate an
24 opportunity to be heard before the joint committee.
25 (b) Except as provided in subsection (c), at the conclusion of its
26 public hearings{ within 30 calendar days after the first meeting of the
27 joint committee}, the joint committee shall introduce a concurrent
28 resolution in each house recommending three persons as candidates to fill
29 the vacancy. No member of the joint committee shall be recommended as
30 a candidate to fill the vacancy.
31 (c) If the joint committee concludes its public hearings while the
32 legislature is not in regular or special session, then{, within 30 calendar
33 days after the first meeting of the joint committee,} the joint committee
34 shall submit a report to the governor recommending three persons as
35 candidates to fill the vacancy.
36 New Sec. 4. (a) Each house shall consider any concurrent resolution
37 that is introduced pursuant to section 3, and amendments thereto, within 10
38 days and shall either adopt such resolution or direct the joint committee to
39 reconvene to reconsider candidates to fill the vacancy.
40 (b) When directed to do so by the legislature, the joint committee
41 shall reconvene and act in accordance with section 3, and amendments
42 thereto. When introducing any second or subsequent resolution, the joint
43 committee may recommend one or more of the candidates who were

